hi paul,
below is the documentation of what i did. i figured that it doesn't make sense to post it on the list before you update the website. but maybe it helps you in checking what i did. well, i'll have a beer now!
ciao thomas
i finally completed the transformation of the documentation from the old kowari version to the new mulgara one. where "completed" is a very relative term... basically i removed a lot of superfluous presentational code, consolidated the navigation in one file per directory and adjusted the layout to that of the mulgara website. i also did some restructuring of the site and threw out some navigational elements. instead of a cms the site now relies on server side includes (an apache httpd mechanism) to ensure a minimum of flexibilty and comfort.
i had to do a lot of search&replace and it may well be that i accidently deleted or changed stuff on the way. so please check the site for those errors.
still not finished is the styling - it works, but could be nicer - and the code of the content parts - that code looks quite awful but can only be corrected by hand. i will continue to work on the stylesheets but, frankly, i would like not to look at the source code of the content pages in the near future ;-)
i also renamed all the pages from numbers to slightly more intuitive names. below is a list of the names before/after. and they end in .html now.
there are some spots where others have to have a look:
- licensing is a little bit broken there are four places where licensing is mentioned legal.html legalinfo.html license.html semanticstore.html some links points to osl 3.o while the text says osl 1.1 another link points to mozilla license i didn't want to touch that stuff, but someone should
- overview/krule.html contains northrop grumman copyright statement. is that okay?
- is putting overview/krule.html into the overview section okay?
- descriptorhw.html contains tucana screenshots. is that okay legally?
- the overview sections contains some documents that could be consolidated, like eg the legal informations. overview/tools.html could be removed. overview/index contains also documentation.htm someone should have a look but overall i think it's structure is already much better than that of the old version
- someone should check the metadata in the head what to do with the dc.creator tom adams? what to do with the dc.contributor? what about the copyright statement? despite my first impression the description and keyword metadata are not very detailed... for more details on changes see below
- i had a problem with 187.htm (now select.html). i guess andrae was the last to edit it. could you please have a look yourself and eventually ... (sorry!)
- i worked on a checkout from last saturday. since i handled this checkout unappropriatly i can't tell if any changes to the pages have been made since then. i can only say that if changes where made, they where not transferred to the new site :-( but they are not lost but got backuped to trunk/docs/oldSite :-D subversion is not really my world...
finally, some words about adding new pages:
- there is a file called http://docs.mulgara.org/template.html (also available from svn https://mulgara.org/svn/mulgara/trunk/docs/site) which should be used as a template (surprise!) for new pages. please follow the directions therin about adding title, keywords and innerpage navigation. additionally to be visible to the public the page has to be added to the navigation, which is done by editing the file "includeTOC.inc" within the same directory the new page resides in(!). there is one includeToc.inc per directory and they get included into the site recursively. there is a navigation on the lefthand side of each page and a page called toc.html, which contains all pages and all innerpage navigations. they are both constructed from the same incudesTOC-files. that way you only have to edit the navigation one time - a solution that i'm quite proud of ;-) i hope it actually works for you... adding a new directory within the root directory is not very hard either, just some cut&paste... well, that may not be entirely true, but i'm too lazy to really explain it. just ask me if you run into problems
ciao thomas
